passages.text: August 31, 2025 08:20 PM GMT
Upside surprise in QE Jun- 25 real GDP pushes F26 growth higher to \(6.7\%\) with nominal growth expected to be weaker at \(8.3\%\) . Risks from external demand could be offset by GST rate cuts.

Real GDP exceeds expectations while nominal growth remains subpar: Real GDP growth for QE Jun- 25 at \(7.8\%\) YoY was higher than MSE at \(6.8\%\) and consensus at \(6.7\%\) , accelerating from \(7.4\%\) in QE Mar- 25. Further, the supply- side or GVA estimate was stronger than expected at \(7.6\%\) vs. MSE of \(6.5\%\) and consensus of \(6.4\%\) . As such, while real growth was stronger than expected, the nominal growth trend moderated, reflecting the outsized impact of a weaker deflator impacting real growth. Indeed, nominal growth moderated to \(8.8\%\) in QE Jun- 25 from \(10.8\%\) in QE Mar- 25. While high- frequency growth indicators remained mixed in QE Jun- 25, nominal corporate revenue growth moderated from last quarter.

A few factors led to the sharp upside in real GDP growth: (i) impact of deflator, which moderated to a 23- quarter low of \(0.9\%\) YoY in QE Jun, boosted the real growth trend and supported corporate margins through lower input price pressures; (ii) front- loaded government spending, with both revenue ex interest spending up \(6.9\%\) YoY in QE Jun and capex spending up \(52\%\) in QE Jun; (iii) front- loaded exports to the US - exports to the US grew \(22\%\) in QE Jun, supporting trade growth; and (iv) impact from low base effect as growth slipped to \(6.5\%\) in QE Jun- 24.

What is the outlook for the remaining quarters of F2026? Notwithstanding the upside surprise in QE Jun, we see the path ahead showing moderation in the real growth trend. We expect some factors to be less supportive; for example, we expect government spending to moderate post- front- loaded spending in QE Jun, the impact of the deflator to reverse in 2HF26 as inflation picks up, the drag from external demand to rise driven by the impact of higher tariffs, and the base to normalize. On the positive side, we expect impending GST tax cuts, the upcoming festive season and strong trends in rural demand to provide a fillip to domestic demand. As such, we expect the composition of growth to change with public spending softening, external demand weakening (mainly goods exports) and private sector demand picking up. We estimate that the incremental drag from external demand at \(\sim 50\) bps could potentially be offset from likely GST cuts, which could boost growth by \(\sim 50\) bps.

From a quarterly perspective, even as we expect QE Sept growth to be around \(7\%\) (helped by base effect and deflator), we expect 2H growth to moderate to around \(6.1\%\) . For F2026, we revise real GDP growth upwards to \(6.7\%\) YoY from \(6.2\%\) YoY earlier, mainly reflecting the boost from QE Jun data. On a nominal basis, we

expect growth at \(8.3\%\) in F2026 vs. \(9.8\%\) in F2025.

What about policy response? While real growth has surpassed expectations in QE June and may present upside risks to the RBI's growth forecast, we believe there is still room for continued easing. In our assessment, low nominal growth indicative of low inflation, prolonged tariff risks, core- core inflation remaining below \(4\%\) for the past 21 months, and real growth expected to moderate to \(6.1\%\) in the second half all suggest that the RBI can maintain its supportive stance on growth. We maintain our view of an additional rate cut in QE December, potentially delayed to the December policy meeting as the RBI monitors high- frequency data to evaluate the impact of tariffs vs. offset from potential GST cuts.

Key monitorables: We watch trends in (1) bilateral trade and tariff- related developments with the US; (2) implications of rationlisation of GST rates on domestic demand; and (3) Fed's easing path and DXY.

GDP growth improved to \(7.8\%\) YoY in QE Jun- 25, up from \(7.4\%\) in QE Mar- 25: The internal indicates that both government and private consumption picked up pace to \(7.5\%\) YoY and \(7\%\) YoY, respectively, while gross fixed capital formation moderated to \(7.8\%\) despite remaining healthy relative to last quarter levels. The continued strength in rural demand, supported by a favourable monsoon and sowing cycle, in addition to improved real wages on the back of moderating inflation, has bolstered consumption levels. Moreover, the government has front- loaded expenditure on both the revenue and capital fronts in QE Jun- 25, which has supported consumption and investment levels.

Net exports turned a drag as imports grew at a faster pace than exports, even as the growth rate in exports picked up relative to last quarter levels. The uptick in exports was led by a potential front- loading of exports to the US, ahead of the implementation of the tariffs, while exports to rest of the world slowed in QE Jun- 25.

Nominal GDP growth slowed to \(8.8\%\) YoY in QE Jun- 25 vs. \(10.8\%\) in the last quarter on the back of a weak GDP deflator, which stood at \(0.9\%\) YoY in QE Jun- 25 - its lowest since QE Dec- 19.

Supply- side growth improved to six- quarter high in QE Jun- 25: GVA growth advanced to \(7.6\%\) YoY in QE Jun- 25, up from \(6.8\%\) YoY in QE Mar- 25. The services sector continued to reflect broad- based resilience as it grew \(9.3\%\) YoY in QE Jun- 25 - its highest since Sep- 23. The strength in services growth was led in part by a weak services deflator. Within services, public admin, defense & other services grew the fastest at \(9.8\%\) YoY, followed by financial, real estate & other professional services. Trade, hotels & restaurants also edged up to an eight- quarter high of \(8.6\%\) YoY.

Industrial activity surprised to the upside, touching \(7\%\) YoY, led by strength in manufacturing activity \((7.7\%)\) and potentially buoyed by the front- loading of exports. While construction activity moderated, it remained healthy, growing at \(7.6\%\) YoY with electricity, gas & water down to \(0.5\%\) YoY - its lowest since QE Dec- 20.

Agri growth moderated to a four- quarter low of \(3.7\%\) YoY in QE Jun- 25. The strength in monsoon and the kharif sowing levels indicates resilience in the agri sector, and should likely support buoyant agri growth going forward.
Core GVA growth accelerated to \(8\%\) YoY in 2Q25 from \(6.7\%\) in 1Q25, suggesting resilience in private sector demand.

Nominal GVA slowed to \(8.8\%\) YoY in QE Jun- 25 from \(9.6\%\) in QE Mar- 25. The sector- wise trends suggest a broad- based weakness in the sector- specific deflators, which led to strength in real growth rates, even as nominal growth rates remained tepid. For the services sector, the deflator softened to \(1.9\%\) YoY in QE Jun- 25 - the lowest since QE Sep- 23. Similarly, for industrial activity, while the trend in the deflator has remained largely weak, it further moderated to seven- quarter low of \(0.5\%\) YoY, driven by a sharper decline in the mining activity deflator.
For more details on sector- wise trends, see Appendix: Details of Quarterly Growth Trends.
